{"parse":{"title":"Platonism in Islamic Philosophy","pageid":31458937,"revid":832467192,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>Medieval <a href=\"/wiki/Islamic_philosophy\" title=\"Islamic philosophy\">Islamic philosophy</a> was steeped in both <a href=\"/wiki/Aristotelianism\" title=\"Aristotelianism\">Aristotelianism</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Neoplatonism\" title=\"Neoplatonism\">Neoplatonism</a> from its 9th-century beginnings with <a href=\"/wiki/Al-Kindi\" title=\"Al-Kindi\">Al-Kindi</a>,  but the influence of Neoplatonism becomes more clearly visible in the 10th and 11th centuries with <a href=\"/wiki/Al-Farabi\" title=\"Al-Farabi\">Al-Farabi</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Avicenna\" title=\"Avicenna\">Avicenna</a>. Al-Farabi expanded on Plato\u2019s concept of an ideal city ruled by philosopher-kings to develop a political philosophy that could accommodate the religious and cultural diversity central to Islamic nations.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\nOn the other hand, both <a href=\"/wiki/Al-Ghazali\" title=\"Al-Ghazali\">al-Ghazali</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Ibn_Rushd\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Ibn Rushd\">Ibn Rushd</a> vigorously opposed Neoplatonic views.\n</p><p>The characteristic of Neoplatonic thought in Islamic theology is that of emanation, linking God's transcendence with the corporeal reality of his creation. \nIslamic Neoplatonism was introduced by Al-Farabi, although  Avicenna proved to have the greater influence. Both authors present a complex scheme of emanation.\n</p><p>Islamic Neoplatonism was allowed to flourish in the 10th to early 11th century, but there \nwas a strong reaction against it in the later 11th century, especially from \n<a href=\"/wiki/Al-Ghazali\" title=\"Al-Ghazali\">Al-Ghazali</a>, who represents Islamic theology's \"most biting attack on philosophy\" at the time, and the severest reaction to Neoplatonism in particular (Netton 1998).\nAl-Ghazali's criticism evoked a counter-reaction by <a href=\"/wiki/Ibn_Rushd\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Ibn Rushd\">Ibn Rushd</a>, \nwho wrote a \"systematic rebuttal of al-Ghazali's critique of Greco-Arab philosophy\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> \nWhile Ibn Rushd is trying to defend the possibility of philosophical thought as non-heretical, he does at the same time himself reject  the theses of the Neoplatonist philosophers.<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>After the death of Ibn Rushd in 1198, the debate on Neoplatonism in Islam mostly comes to an end, and survival of Neoplatonic thought within Islam was mostly limited to <a href=\"/wiki/Ismailism\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Ismailism\">Ismailism</a>.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Platonism_in_Islamic_Philosophy&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Druart, Th\u00e9r\u00e8se-Anne. \"Philosophy in Islam.\" In The Cambridge Companion to Medieval Philosophy. Ed. A. S. McGrade. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 2003. Pp. 103-104</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Fakhry,  <i>A History of Islamic Philosophy,</i>, 1983, p. 276.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">'more often than not...does not, in fact, defend al-Farabi and Ibn Sina.... Instead, he shows to what extent they have departed from the authentic Aristotelian philosophical doctrines, and sometimes joins his voice with that of Ghazali in convicting them of heresy' (Bello 1989: 15).</span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n<ul><li>Netton, Ian Richard. 'Neoplatonism in Islamic Philosophy'. Routledge Encyclopedia of Philosophy, 1998. <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external autonumber\" href=\"http://www.muslimphilosophy.com/ip/rep/H003.htm\">[1]</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"External_links\">External links</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Platonism_in_Islamic_Philosophy&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: External links\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Henry_Corbin\" title=\"Henry Corbin\">Henry Corbin</a>, History of Islamic philosophy <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://web.archive.org/web/20080509183618/http://www.amiscorbin.com/textes/anglais/Hist_Iran_Phil_Corbin_part_I.pdf\">part one</a>, <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://web.archive.org/web/20100326193125/http://www.amiscorbin.com/textes/anglais/Hist_Iran_Phil_Corbin_p2.pdf\">part two</a></li>\n<li><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.iep.utm.edu/neoplato/\">Neoplatonism</a> entry in the <i><a href=\"/wiki/Internet_Encyclopedia_of_Philosophy\" title=\"Internet Encyclopedia of Philosophy\">Internet Encyclopedia of Philosophy</a></i></li>\n<li><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.muslimphilosophy.com/ip/rep/H021.htm\">Abu Nasr al-Farabi at muslimphilosophy.com</a></li>\n<li><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.iep.utm.edu/avicenna/\">Avicenna</a> entry by Sajjad H. Rizvi in the <i><a href=\"/wiki/Internet_Encyclopedia_of_Philosophy\" title=\"Internet Encyclopedia of Philosophy\">Internet Encyclopedia of Philosophy</a></i></li>\n<li><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.john-uebersax.com/plato/ip.htm\">Islamic Platonists and Neoplatonists</a></li></ul>\n\n<!-- \nNewPP limit report\nParsed by mw2194\nCached time: 20180920134010\nCache expiry: 1900800\nDynamic content: false\nCPU time usage: 0.024 seconds\nReal time usage: 0.034 seconds\nPreprocessor visited node count: 114/1000000\nPreprocessor generated node count: 0/1500000\nPost\u2010expand include size: 377/2097152 bytes\nTemplate argument size: 95/2097152 bytes\nHighest expansion depth: 7/40\nExpensive parser function count: 0/500\nUnstrip recursion depth: 0/20\nUnstrip post\u2010expand size: 1246/5000000 bytes\nNumber of Wikibase entities loaded: 0/400\nLua time usage: 0.003/10.000 seconds\nLua memory usage: 525 KB/50 MB\n-->\n<!--\nTransclusion expansion time report (%,ms,calls,template)\n100.00%   18.604      1 Template:Reflist\n100.00%   18.604      1 -total\n 11.14%    2.072      1 Template:Main_other\n-->\n\n<!-- Saved in parser cache with key enwiki:pcache:idhash:31458937-0!canonical and timestamp 20180920134010 and revision id 832467192\n -->\n</div>"},"langlinks":[],"categories":[{"sortkey":"Platonism In Islamic Philosophy","*":"Neoplatonism"},{"sortkey":"Platonism In Islamic Philosophy","*":"History_of_philosophy"},{"sortkey":"Platonism In Islamic Philosophy","*":"Early_Islamic_philosophy"}],"links":[{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Al-Farabi"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Al-Ghazali"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Al-Kindi"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Aristotelianism"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Avicenna"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Henry Corbin"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Ibn Rushd"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Internet Encyclopedia of Philosophy"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Islamic philosophy"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Ismailism"},{"ns":0,"exists":"","*":"Neoplatonism"}],"templates":[{"ns":10,"exists":"","*":"Template:Reflist"},{"ns":10,"exists":"","*":"Templat